# Nihongoes conventions

## Courses (N5–N1 + Frontend)
- Author lesson content (vocab, phrases, grammar, reading, reference) by hand in each `<course>/index.ts` (or its `lessons-*.ts` part files) following the shape of the existing lessons. Do NOT use a code generator for lesson data. When listing a lesson's vocabulary, cross-check against the Minna no Nihongo word list so nothing is missed (see the "never list less than the textbook" rule) - use the textbook/an authoritative list as a reference while you write, but keep our own EN/VI meanings.
- Lesson count per level is NOT fixed — author enough lessons to cover the full standard JLPT grammar syllabus for that level; reorder/renumber lessons freely. See the `n5-course` rule for details.
- Keep frontend/software-engineering Japanese content in a dedicated top-level `frontend` course track; do NOT mix frontend lessons into JLPT levels (`n5`-`n1`).
- In `src/constants/courses`, keep one folder per course level/track (`n5`, `n4`, `n3`, `n2`, `n1`, `frontend`), with each course definition in `<course>/index.ts`; keep the `courses/` root as registry/types only.
- Store split lesson part files inside each corresponding course folder (e.g. `src/constants/courses/n2/lessons-*.ts`, `src/constants/courses/frontend/lessons-*.ts`) instead of at the `courses/` root.

## Kanji track (IMPORTANT)
- The standalone Kanji feature is a hub -> track -> lesson tree, separate from the JLPT courses: `/kanji` (hub, lists kanji collections/tracks), `/kanji/:track` (track overview, lists lessons), `/kanji/:track/lesson/:lessonId` (detail), plus `/quiz` and `/writing` under the lesson. Data is in `src/constants/kanji/` (`types.ts`, `lessons.ts`, `index.ts`); pages under `src/pages/kanji/` (`index.tsx` hub, `track/`, `lesson/`, `quiz/`, `writing/`).
- Kanji tracks are organized BY SCHOOL GRADE (Jōyō grade), one track per grade: `grade-1` ("Grade 1 kanji" / "Kanji lớp 1", 80 chars = 8 lessons), `grade-2` ("Grade 2 kanji" / "Kanji lớp 2", 160 chars = 16 lessons), etc. Do NOT lump every grade into one giant "Jōyō" track. In `lessons.ts` keep one exported array per grade (`grade1Lessons`, `grade2Lessons`, ...), each independently wrapped in `withSequentialNumbers(...)` so every grade's lessons number from 1; `index.ts` builds one `KanjiTrack` per grade array. Add the next grade by appending a `gradeNLessons` array + a `gradeNTrack`.
- Radicals: the 214 Kangxi radicals (部首) live in `src/constants/kanji/radicals.ts` (`Radical { number, char, variants?, strokes, name (romaji), kana (Japanese name in kana), meaning }`). The radical card + legend DISPLAY the Japanese name in `kana` (not the romaji `name`); keep `name` as the romaji reference. Shown at `/kanji/radicals` (`src/pages/kanji/radicals/index.tsx`) grouped by stroke count. Linked from the hub page and a "Radicals"/"Bộ thủ" nav child. The static `/kanji/radicals` route is registered before `/kanji/:track` (React Router ranks it higher anyway).
- Radical meaning vs mnemonic consistency (IMPORTANT): a kanji card shows each component radical's card meaning as a pill, so a mnemonic must NOT describe that radical with a sense the card doesn't list. Many radicals carry a different sense when used as a building block than their headword meaning (e.g. 尸 corpse -> roof/dwelling; 自 self -> nose; 又 again -> hand; 寸 inch -> hand; 月 moon -> flesh/body; 欠 lack -> open mouth/yawn). When a mnemonic relies on such a component-sense, ADD it to that radical's `meaning` (both en/vi) as a second clause: en `... (when used in other kanji)`, vi `...; <nghĩa> (khi ghép chữ)` - this propagates to every kanji using it. If instead the glyph is a corrupted/false radical (e.g. the 田 in 思 is a head 囟, not a field), do NOT list it in `components` (drop the misleading pill) and just describe it in the mnemonic (e.g. "the head, drawn like 田").
- Tracks are a registry: `KanjiTrack { slug, name, subtitle, intro, lessons }` in `kanji/index.ts` (`kanjiTracks`, `getKanjiTrack`). All path helpers are track-aware: `kanjiTrackPath(slug)`, `kanjiLessonPath(slug, id)`, `kanjiQuizPath(slug, id)`, `kanjiWritingPath(slug, id)`; `getKanjiLesson(slug, id)`. Pages read both `:track` and `:lessonId` params. Add a new collection by pushing another `KanjiTrack`.
- Split each grade's Jōyō kanji into hand-authored, ordered lessons (grade 1 lesson 1 = numbers 一〜十). ~10 characters per lesson is a loose target, NOT a hard rule - a lesson may have more or fewer so it stays thematically coherent; do NOT create a "leftover/assorted/bổ sung" dump lesson, distribute odd characters into the best-fitting themed lesson instead. Never state a fixed "10 per lesson" count in copy, comments, or docs. Wrap each grade's array with `withSequentialNumbers(...)` so `id`/`number` auto-assign; add lessons by appending blocks to that grade's array.
- Each `KanjiEntry` has `char`, bilingual `meaning`, `onyomi` (katakana), `kunyomi` (hiragana, okurigana after a dot e.g. `ひと.つ`), `components` (the radical/part chars making up the kanji, e.g. `['亻','木']`; shown via `getRadicalByChar` -> the 214-radical data). The card renders the "Bộ thủ" row ONLY when a kanji clearly decomposes into 2+ radicals (`components.length >= 2`); for primitives or kanji that don't cleanly break into radicals, use `[]` (or a single item - it won't be shown) so no misleading single/partial radical appears. The `KanjiEntry.mnemonic` field still exists in the type but is REMOVED project-wide and DEPRECATED per the user's decision - do NOT add `mnemonic` to any kanji (too many were forced/contrived). Leave it unset everywhere.
- The full single-kanji study card is the shared `<KanjiCard entry index />` component (`src/components/kanji-card/index.tsx`) - reuse it, do NOT re-render kanji details inline. an OPTIONAL bilingual `note` (usage caveat - reading choices, common confusions, when to use which reading; add it whenever a kanji has a real usage gotcha, e.g. 四 usually よん not し), and `examples`. The card shows `mnemonic`/`note` only when present. Display kun okurigana as `base（okuri）`; speak readings with the dot stripped. Do NOT show a raw stroke count (low learning value on its own); a future stroke-order animation would be the useful upgrade instead.
- Store a `KanjiEntry.meaning.vi` (and `Radical.meaning.vi`) as `Hán-Việt - nghĩa` (e.g. 木 -> `mộc - cây, gỗ`, 犬 -> `khuyển - chó`). At DISPLAY time it is rendered as `[Hán-Việt] nghĩa` (bracketed + capitalized) via `formatKanjiMeaning(...)` from `@/constants/kanji` - apply it to the VI meaning wherever a kanji/radical meaning is shown (kanji card, radical pills, radicals page). `meaning.en` stays the plain English meaning (unchanged by the formatter). Example-word meanings (`KanjiExample.meaning`) are word meanings and do NOT take a Hán-Việt prefix or formatting.
- Write the kanji `meaning` reasonably COMPLETE, not overly terse: cover the main senses in a natural phrase (e.g. 用 -> `dụng - dùng, sử dụng; việc, công việc cần làm`, not `dụng - dùng; việc`). Separate distinct senses with `;`.
- The number of example words per kanji is FLEXIBLE - author as many as make sense for that character (cover its important on/kun readings; don't pad to a fixed count). Do NOT normalize every kanji to the same number of examples.
- Each example is `{ parts: { text, reading }[], meaning }`: split the word so every kanji is its own part paired with the exact kana it reads as (e.g. 一月 -> 一/いち + 月/がつ), okurigana kana is its own part (つ/つ), and special whole-word readings (jukujikun like 二十歳=はたち) stay one part. Derive the spoken text and surface word by joining the parts; the lesson page shows the word plus the joined reading in grey (no per-kanji color coding). Do NOT store a separate flat `reading`/`word`.
- Wiring mirrors courses: register `/kanji` in `routes.ts`, add both-locale routes in `app.tsx`, a `kanjiGroup` nav group in `nav-items.ts`, `KANJI_SITEMAP_PATHS` in `generate-sitemap.ts`, a `kanji` prefix case in `getSeoRouteKey`, and `seo.kanji` + `kanji.*` i18n keys (en + vi).
- Kanji page headers (lesson/quiz/writing) do NOT use a back button; navigation is via clickable outlined `Chip`s in a wrap row: a secondary track chip (-> `kanjiTrackPath`) + a primary lesson chip (-> `kanjiLessonPath`), plus a context chip (e.g. "Luyện viết") on quiz/writing. The lesson detail page also has prev/next lesson buttons at the bottom (reuse `course.previousLesson`/`course.nextLesson`, hidden at the ends). This intentionally overrides the generic "back button on its own row" header rule for kanji pages.
- Each kanji lesson has 2 practice exercises: a meaning quiz (`/kanji/lesson/:id/quiz`) and writing (`/kanji/lesson/:id/writing`). The quiz (`src/pages/kanji/quiz/index.tsx`) combines BOTH directions - "kanji -> meaning" and "meaning -> kanji" - in ONE page with a `ToggleButtonGroup` (switching remounts the inner quiz via `key`); it reuses the course `ChoiceButton` + the standard retry-until-correct + 900ms auto-advance + result-screen pattern (reuse `course.*` result/progress i18n). Writing reuses the shared `<TracingCanvas>` (`src/components/tracing-canvas/index.tsx`, extracted from the course writing page so both tracks share it). Link both from a `KanjiPracticePanel` (flex-wrap buttons) on the lesson detail page.

## Git (IMPORTANT)
- NEVER commit or push on your own. Only run `git commit` / `git push` when the user explicitly asks. Make and validate changes in the working tree and wait for the user's go-ahead before committing.
- NEVER merge a PR (`gh pr merge`) on your own. Merging is destructive/hard-to-undo — always ask for an explicit, per-PR confirmation right before merging, even if an earlier instruction seemed to allow it. Preparing a PR (rebase, resolve conflicts, push, make it green) is fine; clicking merge is not, without confirmation.

## Dev tooling (IMPORTANT)
- The repo requires Node 24 (`.nvmrc`). The default shell may resolve `node` to v12, which breaks `pnpm`. Always prefix commands:
  `export NVM_DIR="$HOME/.nvm" && source "$NVM_DIR/nvm.sh" && nvm use 24 >/dev/null && pnpm ...`
- Validate changes with `pnpm run typecheck`, `pnpm run lint`, `pnpm run format` (or `pnpm run check`).
- Prettier `trailingComma: "none"` — do NOT add trailing commas after the last element/param/property; `prettier --write` enforces this repo-wide.
- `pnpm-lock.yaml` is in `.prettierignore` — never let `pnpm run format` reformat it (it caused a huge spurious diff once). Don't commit lockfile changes unless `package.json` actually changed.

## Imports (IMPORTANT)
- NO parent-relative imports (`../...`). Use the `@/` alias for anything outside the current folder; only same-folder `./...` relative imports are allowed (e.g. a page importing its colocated `./course-quiz.ts`). This is enforced by ESLint `no-restricted-imports` (patterns `../*`, `../**`) in `eslint.config.js`.
- Components/pages are folder-based (`<name>/index.tsx`), so import them extensionless via the alias: `@/components/speak-button`, `@/pages/course/shared`.

## Lint rules to respect
- Prettier runs INSIDE ESLint via `eslint-plugin-prettier` (the `prettier/prettier` rule, wired through `eslint-plugin-prettier/recommended` in `eslint.config.js`). This means formatting problems show up as red ESLint errors in the editor and fail `pnpm run lint` (not just `format:check`). Run `pnpm run lint:fix` (or `prettier --write`) to fix. Note: `@stylistic` alone canNOT replicate Prettier (no print-width line wrapping) — `prettier/prettier` is what enforces full formatting parity.
- `react-hooks/set-state-in-effect`: do NOT call `setState` inside `useEffect`. To reset component state when a prop/route/locale changes, remount via `key` (e.g. `<Quiz key={`${id}:${locale}`} />`) and reset on user actions in event handlers instead.
- `useEffect` is fine for syncing with external systems (e.g. calling `speakJapanese`), just not for setting React state.
- Enforce semicolons for code style: keep Prettier `semi: true` and ESLint `semi: ['error', 'always']` (for `ts`/`tsx` and `scripts/**/*.mjs`). The core `semi` rule does NOT cover TS type/interface member delimiters — those are enforced separately by `@stylistic/member-delimiter-style` (from `@stylistic/eslint-plugin`), configured to `semi` (multiline `requireLast: true`, singleline) to match Prettier.
- For conditional JSX *content* rendering, always use `&&`, never the `? :` ternary — including when there is an else branch. Split a two-branch render into two guards: `{cond && (<A />)}{!cond && (<B />)}`. This applies to `: null` cases too. Exception: keep `? :` for non-JSX *value* selection (prop values like `color={x ? 'a' : 'b'}`, `state={a ? 'x' : 'y'}`, string pickers like `{cond ? t('a') : t('b')}`) since `&&` cannot express those.

## Kana terminology (display text)
- In ALL user-facing display text (UI labels, chart headings/descriptions, exercise hints, meta descriptions) use the colloquial mark names: call dakuten "Tenten" and handakuten "Maru". Do NOT use the formal words "dakuten"/"handakuten" in any displayed copy (EN or VI). Internal code identifiers (variable/type/scope keys like `dakuten`, `handakuten`, `scopeDakuten`) stay as-is.

## Vocab word display (IMPORTANT)
- When a word HAS a kanji form, render it inline as `漢字（かな）` - kanji first, then the kana reading in full-width Japanese parentheses. A kana-only word (no kanji, or kanji === kana) renders plainly. No underline, no furigana. This is implemented in `VocabHeadword` (`src/pages/course/lesson-page/index.tsx`), used by the vocab and reference sections. Do NOT revert to the old two-line (kanji on top, grey kana below) layout.

## Text & typography (IMPORTANT)
- Use ONLY US-keyboard ASCII punctuation in non-Japanese text (UI strings, EN/VI content, code, comments, docs). NEVER use em dash (`—`) or en dash (`–`); use a hyphen `-` (as a separator write ` - `, for ranges write `N5-N1` not `N5–N1`). Avoid other "smart"/typographic unicode (curly quotes `“”‘’`, ellipsis `…`) too: use `"`, `'`, `...`.
- Japanese CONTENT may use Japanese punctuation (`、。「」〜・` etc.); the rule only applies to the non-Japanese parts of a string.
- Minimum text size is `body1` (16px / 1rem) on BOTH mobile and desktop - no readable text may render smaller. Enforced centrally in `src/theme/app-theme.ts` by flooring the small MUI variants (`body2`, `subtitle2`, `caption`, `overline`, `button`) to `1rem`, plus `MuiChip` (`root` + `sizeSmall`, whose own font is 13px/12px). Do NOT introduce `fontSize` values below `1rem` for text; keep the theme as the single source of truth (only tiny non-text decorations like a numbered badge glyph may stay smaller).

## Alphabet romaji matching
- Each kana accepts EXACTLY ONE romaji - the spelling shown in the chart (`AlphabetCell.romaji`). The romaji quiz's `correctAnswers` is just `[correctItem.romaji]`; typed input is only normalized with `normalizeRomajiInput` (trim + lowercase) before an exact match. Do NOT add alternate-spelling aliasing (no Kunrei si/shi, tya/cha, no homophone fuzziness) in the alphabet quiz.
- Use Hepburn for the homophone kana: ぢ/ヂ = `ji`, づ/ヅ = `zu` (same as じ/ず). This means `ji`/`zu` are duplicated in the chart; `buildRomajiToCharMap` (in `src/constants/alphabet-charts.ts`) is first-occurrence-wins so じ/ず keep those keys and yoon base lookups (じゃ etc.) stay correct.
- The sentence exercise keeps its OWN separate canonicalizer in `sentence/transliterate.ts` - independent of the alphabet quiz.
- Script pairing in the quiz works on bilingual `KanaEntry { romaji, hiragana, katakana }` units (built in `exercise-quiz.ts` by zipping the two same-ordered per-script item arrays). The hiragana<->katakana counterpart is the matching field on the entry - do NOT re-pair by romaji (homophones じ/ぢ, ず/づ share a romaji) or by Unicode code-point math.

## i18n
- UI chrome text lives in `src/i18n/translations.ts` as nested keys; both `en` and `vi` MUST be kept in sync. Read via `const { t, locale } = useTranslation()`.
- Bilingual CONTENT data (Japanese + meanings) is stored in data files as `Record<Locale, string>` (type `Bilingual`) and rendered with `value[locale]`, not as translation keys.
- The header should not show brand logo or slogan; keep only the text brand link in the app bar. The site footer text stays in ENGLISH regardless of locale.
- On desktop (`md` and up), align the text brand (`Nihongoes`) with the main content text column (same left gutter alignment), not visual center of the viewport.

## Documentation
- When the user asks for bilingual docs, write the whole document in parallel EN/VI sections (not only one quick-start block), and keep command examples identical across both languages.
- In user-facing docs, prefer concise commands (`pnpm ...`) and list `nvm use 24` once as a prerequisite instead of prefixing every command with shell setup.

## Audio / pronunciation
- Japanese is spoken via the Web Speech API: `speakJapanese(text)` in `src/utils/speech.ts` (lang `ja-JP`). Voice + speed are user-configurable (persisted in localStorage) via `<AudioSettings />` in the header; voices load async (use `subscribeVoices`).
- Anywhere Japanese text is shown, add `<SpeakButton text={...} />` (`src/components/speak-button/index.tsx`). Pass kana for single words, full sentence for examples. Do NOT add it to quiz answer options (would leak the answer) or to grammar patterns containing `N` placeholders.
- Do not make audio interaction icon-only. Wherever practical, make the related Japanese text/surface itself clickable (and keyboard-accessible with Enter/Space) so users do not need to tap precisely on the speaker icon.
- Default voice: prefer the macOS "O-ren" voice when no user choice is stored (`getDefaultJapaneseVoice` in `src/utils/speech.ts`, matches name containing `o-ren`, else first Japanese voice). Only display/play it — do NOT pin it to localStorage so the default stays adaptive per device.
- When a kana's spoken reading differs from its glyph (particles は=wa, へ=e, を=o), set `speech` on the `VocabItem` (e.g. `speech: 'わ'`) so TTS says the particle reading, not the literal kana. The lesson page speaks `item.speech ?? item.kana`. Full sentences need no override (TTS reads particles correctly in context).

## Surfaces & cards (Material style) — ALWAYS follow
- Prefer elevation/tonal surfaces over borders. Do NOT use `variant="outlined"` for content cards/papers.
- Do NOT use heavy MUI default elevations (`elevation={2}` etc.) — their default shadow has a sharp bottom edge that looks like a thick bottom border. Always use `elevation={0}` + a helper.
- Helpers in `src/theme/surfaces.ts`, applied as `elevation={0}` with `sx={[helper, { ...overrides }]}`:
  - `elevatedSurfaceSx` / `interactiveSurfaceSx` — white + soft shadow (cards, lists, quiz panels; interactive adds hover lift).
  - `subtleSurfaceSx` — neutral grey tonal (secondary/low-emphasis boxes).
  - `tonalSurfaceSx` — primary-tinted tonal (call-to-action surfaces).
- Chrome regions (header, drawer, footer) separate by a soft shadow only — NO background tint and NO divider lines. Header casts the shadow downward, the drawer to the right, the footer upward.
- Buttons/Chips may keep `variant="outlined"` — those are controls, not content surfaces.

## Quiz feedback styling
- Keep answer feedback colors consistent across course quizzes and alphabet quizzes: correct uses a light blue tone, wrong uses a light pink tone (soft fill + soft border, not saturated green/red).
- Do NOT show a "Correct"/"Incorrect" text label or success/error icons; rely on the choice color feedback only.
- Quizzes RETRY until correct, then AUTO-ADVANCE: ~900ms after a correct answer the course exercise/listening/reading (and the alphabet quizzes) move to the next question on their own. A wrong answer just marks that attempt (wrong choice tinted pink and locked, or fill-in field turned red) and lets the user try again - do NOT reveal the correct answer and do NOT show a Next button on a wrong attempt. Provide a separate "Show answer" toggle (reuse `exercise.showAnswer`/`exercise.hideAnswer`, grid-overlay style so it never shifts layout) for fill-in questions instead. Score a question as correct only when it is solved on the first attempt.
- Implement the auto-advance delay with a `setTimeout` inside a `useEffect` (set state in the timer callback, never directly in the effect body).

## Hints / annotations
- Render annotation/hint text (tap-to-play hints, replay hints, etc.) via the shared `<HintText>` component (`src/components/hint-text/index.tsx`): it prefixes the text with `* ` (the asterisk is nudged down to center on the first line), uses `color="error.main"` (red) and medium weight to stand apart from grey body copy. Pass spacing via `sx`. Do NOT hand-roll hint `Typography`.

## Kanji cards - components & examples (IMPORTANT)
- Each `KanjiEntry` may declare `parts: KanjiComponent[]` (`{ char, role }`, role = `radical` | `semantic` | `phonetic` | `other`) - the FULL component breakdown. `KanjiCard` renders these as color-coded chips: bộ thủ chính = blue (`radical`), gợi nghĩa = green (`semantic`), gợi âm = orange (`phonetic`), khác = grey (`other`). Colors live in `src/theme/kanji-component-colors.ts`; the legend is `<KanjiComponentLegend>` on the lesson page.
- ALWAYS show the main radical (bộ thủ chính) on every card. `ComponentsRow` (in `kanji-card`) resolves: authored `parts` first; else if the char is itself a radical (`getRadicalByChar`) show `[{char,'radical'}]`; else derive from legacy `components`. When authoring `parts`, include EXACTLY ONE `radical` role. If the dictionary radical is the whole char (self-radical like 木/山/見/石), don't author `parts` - let the auto-fallback show the self radical (don't list the sub-strokes).
- Chips always display in role order radical -> semantic -> phonetic -> other (sorted in `ComponentsRow`), regardless of authored order.
- Info rows (Meaning / Components / On'yomi / Kun'yomi) share ONE CSS grid (`gridTemplateColumns: 'auto 1fr'`) so the label column auto-sizes to the widest label - never hard-code a label `minWidth`.
- When authoring a kanji's `radical` role, the char MUST be its true Kangxi (classical) radical, not just any visible piece (e.g. 帰 -> 止 not 巾; 書 -> 曰; 医 -> 匸; 胃 -> 肉; 才 -> 手). Verify against KANJIDIC2: `radical.classical` in a joyo dataset (e.g. jkindrix/japanese-language-data `data/core/kanji-joyo.json`). Do NOT trust memory for simplified/atomic kanji where the radical is not a visible sub-part.
- Example words must NOT be a single kanji equal to the headword that just repeats its meaning (e.g. 冬 -> ふゆ "winter"). Replace such standalone examples with a real compound word that keeps the SAME reading morpheme (e.g. 冬休み ふゆやすみ; 森 もり -> 青森 あおもり; 車 くるま -> 車いす くるまいす). Rendaku variants (はやし -> 松林 まつばやし) are acceptable when no non-rendaku compound exists.

## Grammar highlighting (IMPORTANT)
- Each `GrammarPoint` declares an EXPLICIT `highlights: HighlightTerm[]` (the grammar morphemes to color, in palette order) - NEVER rely on auto/regex derivation from the pattern. `HighlightTerm` = a `string`, or a `string[]` of alternatives that SHARE one color. Use a shared-color group ONLY for a closed interchangeable set like `['これ','それ','あれ']`; list distinct variants (e.g. `だれ`/`どなた`, `なんさい`/`おいくつ`) as SEPARATE terms so each gets its own color.
- Highlight ONLY grammar components: particles (`は`/`が`/`の`/`も`/`に`...), copula/endings (`です`/`じゃありません`/`ですか`), question words (`なん`/`だれ`/`どこ`/`なんさい`...). Do NOT highlight plain vocabulary or special readings (e.g. `はたち` is a word, not grammar).
- Split a trailing `ですか` into TWO separate color terms `です` and `か` (the copula and the question particle each get their own color) - never group them as one `ですか` term, and never leave them attached to a question word. E.g. `highlights: ['は','なん','です','か']`, not `['は','なん','ですか']` and not `['は','なんですか']`. The pattern string may keep a space (`N は なん ですか`); it still displays attached (`formatGrammarPatternDisplay`).
- When a grammar char accidentally sits inside another word, protect that word with `excludeHighlights: string[]` (matched but never colored): e.g. `['はたち']` so `は` in `はたち` isn't colored; `['この','その','あの','どの']` on a `の` point so only the possessive `の` is colored, not the `の` inside a demonstrative. Analyze each example and exclude as needed.
- Companion answers live in the point's `answers` block (`{ explanation?, examples, highlights?, excludeHighlights? }`), rendered as a separate labelled "Answers"/"Cách trả lời" sub-block with its OWN `highlights`. `GrammarPointCard` shifts the answer block's palette by the number of question highlight groups (`colorOffset={point.highlights.length}`) so answer colors never reuse the question's colors.
- Colors come from `GRAMMAR_HIGHLIGHT_PALETTE` (10 distinct hex hues) in `src/utils/grammar-highlight.ts`; no red (error), keep hues clearly different. `<GrammarHighlightedText>` takes `highlights` / `exclude` / `colorOffset` props (NOT a raw pattern); `splitHighlightedText(text, highlights, exclude?)` is the underlying splitter.

## Scrollbars
- Use one unified thin scrollbar style across the app. Global/page scrollbars and local scroll containers (e.g. drawer/menu lists) must use the same `thin-scrollbar` appearance defined in `src/index.css`.

## Page layout
- Wrap every page's content in the shared `<PageContainer>` (`src/components/page-container/index.tsx`) — do NOT use `<Container>` directly in pages. Content width/padding live in `PageContainer` + the `MuiContainer` theme overrides in `main.tsx`, with a global max width of `1200px`.
- On desktop, keep app bar inner content constrained to the same `1200px` max width and gutter alignment as page content.
- Page headers: put the back button on its own row (wrapped in a `Box`), then the lesson/section chip, then the title — never let the back button and chip share a line.
- Keep page-level `h1` typography visually consistent across pages (same size + weight). Use the shared `Heading` component with `component="h1"` and no per-page font-size overrides.
- Keep heading weights consistent for `h2`/`h3` title text as well (page sections and card/list titles should use `fontWeight: 600` unless there is a deliberate, documented exception).

## Component reuse (IMPORTANT)
- ALWAYS reuse shared components instead of duplicating or re-rendering the same UI inline. Before writing a piece of UI, check whether a component already exists (e.g. `KanjiCard`, `TracingCanvas`, `SpeakableSurface`, `SpeakButton`, `Heading`, `HintText`, `PageContainer`, `ChoiceButton`, `KanjiReadingsNote`) and use it.
- When the same UI/logic is (or will be) used in 2+ places, extract it into a folder-based shared component under `src/components/<name>/index.tsx` (or a shared page-segment folder for page-only reuse) and import it via the `@/` alias - do NOT copy-paste. Keep a single source of truth.

## Component props typing
- ALWAYS declare props as a named `type <ComponentName>Props = { ... }` above the component (above its doc comment, if any) and annotate the param with it (e.g. `function Foo({ a, b }: FooProps)`). NEVER inline an object type in the parameter list - not even a single-prop one-liner like `({ level }: { level: CourseLevel })`. For generics use `type FooProps<T> = { ... }` + `function Foo<T>({ ... }: FooProps<T>)`.

## Buttons / icon hit areas
- NEVER stretch an `IconButton` (or any round button) with `top: 0; bottom: 0` / `height: 100%` or otherwise give it an unequal width vs height - its hover/ripple background turns into an oval. Keep a square footprint and center it instead, e.g. absolutely positioned use `top: '50%'` + `transform: 'translateY(-50%)'` (not `top:0; bottom:0; my:'auto'`).
- COMMON GOTCHA: when an `IconButton`/`SpeakButton` sits as a child of a `display: flex` row (e.g. a `SpeakableSurface` card with icon + text block), the default `align-items: stretch` stretches the button to the row's full height -> oval hover. ALWAYS set `alignItems: 'flex-start'` (or `'center'`) on that flex container, or `alignSelf` on the button. Mirror the lesson vocab card: `sx={{ p: 1.5, display: 'flex', gap: 0.5, alignItems: 'flex-start' }}`.

## MUI icons
- Import by exact file name (often the `Outlined` suffix, e.g. `CheckCircleOutlined` not `CheckCircleOutline`). If unsure, check `node_modules/@mui/icons-material/`.

## Storybook
- Colocate the story next to its component as `<name>/index.stories.tsx` (folder-based, mirroring `<name>/index.tsx`) — do NOT repeat the component name in the filename (no `footer.stories.tsx`).
- Title stories generically by folder: `Components/<ComponentName>` for everything under `src/components/`. Don't hand-pick ad-hoc categories (no `Layout/...`).
- Global providers (MUI theme + `CssBaseline`, `LanguageProvider`, router) live in `.storybook/preview.tsx` decorators; the MUI theme is shared via `src/theme/app-theme.ts` (imported by both `main.tsx` and the preview). A `locale` toolbar global switches en/vi (remount `LanguageProvider` via `key`).

## Routing & sitemap
- Routes map to `src/pages/**/index.tsx`. Static routes live in `src/constants/routes.ts`; dynamic param routes are registered in `src/app.tsx`.
- For dynamic pages, export path arrays from the data file and append them to `SITEMAP_PATHS` in `routes.ts`.

## Navigation labels
- In drawer sub-items for course lessons, keep lesson number inline with the lesson name (e.g. `Lesson 1: ...` / `Bài 1: ...`); do not render the number as a separate left icon/symbol.
- Keep English lesson chips/menu wording consistent as `Lesson` (e.g. `Lesson {{number}}` in `course.lessonLabel` and `Lesson N: ...` in drawer sub-items), matching the `/lesson/...` route and the Vietnamese `Bài`. Do NOT use `Unit`.

## Drawer menu layout
- Keep drawer menu visuals minimal: use subtle divider lines between sibling items/sub-items; avoid card-like shadows/background blocks for separation.
- Do not apply hover background fills on menu items/sub-items. Keep hover visually neutral and use selected state only for active location.
- Keep child item rows at consistent height even when some labels wrap to two lines (uniform row height for scanability).
- Maintain alignment consistency: course lesson sub-item text starts align with parent item text starts; for alphabet sub-items, align child icons to the same horizontal start as the parent text column.
